 Sometimes when we feel lost, doing the things we love which make us who we are , is our last resort. For me, it has been either cooking or drawing or dancing. node.text:
?At the beginning of July, Pfizer/BioNTech revealed early positive data from their mRNA-based COVID-19 vaccine program. Those results demonstrated that one of the candidates, BNT162b1, generated promising dose-dependent immunogenicity. The companies also announced that another candidate, BNT162b2, had been selected for a large-scale, phase 3 clinical trial.?
?
In additional data shared recently, Pfizer/BioNTech posted the results from all 332 participants tested with the two mRNA-based candidates, BNT162b1 or BNT162b2, to clarify their decision. That data showed that systemic events following administration of BNT162b were milder compared to those experienced with BNT162b1. Following the second dose of BNT162b2, only 17% of participants in the 18-55 years age group reported fever, compared to 75% in the same age group in the BNT162b1 arm.?
?
"It is important to us to continue sharing data and related information on our COVID-19 vaccine lead candidate," said Ugur Sahin, CEO, and Co-Founder of BioNTech and a 2019 Mustafa(pbuh) Prize laureate. "The favorable safety profile of BNT162b2 and the breadth of T cell responses we previously announced have supported our decision to select this candidate for the pivotal Phase 2/3 study. As of today, we have already dosed more than 11,000 participants with BNT162b2 in that study."?
?
If all goes to plan in this study, the companies have said they are on track to file for regulatory review for BNT162b2 as early as October and plan to supply up to 100 million doses globally by the end of the year if approval is obtained.?
.?
.?
.?
